hands_on_practices.solution:
At the triple point, the sublimation and vaporization curves intersect, so the vapor pressures are equal. Equating the given empirical relations,
$$
\log_{10}(P)=4.63-\frac{402}{T}=3.90-\frac{341}{T}.
$$
Set the right-hand sides equal and solve for $T$:
$$
4.63-\frac{402}{T}=3.90-\frac{341}{T}
\;\Rightarrow\;
4.63-3.90=\frac{402-341}{T}
\;\Rightarrow\;
0.73=\frac{61}{T}
\;\Rightarrow\;
T=\frac{61}{0.73}=\frac{6100}{73}\ \text{K}.
$$
Substitute $T=\frac{6100}{73}$ into either expression for $\log_{10}(P)$. Using the solid-vapor form,
$$
\log_{10}(P)=4.63-\frac{402}{T}
= \frac{463}{100}-\frac{402}{6100/73}
= \frac{463 \cdot 61}{6100}-\frac{402\cdot 73}{6100}
= \frac{28243}{6100}-\frac{29346}{6100}
= -\frac{1103}{6100}.
$$
Therefore,
$$
P=10^{-\frac{1103}{6100}}.
$$
Now evaluate numerically and round to three significant figures:
$T_{tp}=\frac{6100}{73}\approx 83.6\ \text{K}$, and
$P_{tp}=10^{-\frac{1103}{6100}}\approx 0.659\ \text{atm}.$
Thus, the triple point as a row matrix (temperature, pressure) is as follows.
